cloud computing

‚òÅÔ∏è Cloud Deployment Models in AWS
Public Cloud
Definition: Services are offered over the internet by third-party providers like AWS.
Characteristics:
Shared infrastructure.
Scalable and cost-effective.
Ideal for startups and general-purpose workloads.
AWS Example: EC2 instances running in public subnets.

Private Cloud
Definition: Cloud infrastructure is dedicated to a single organization.
Characteristics:
Greater control and security.
Can be hosted on-premises or via AWS (e.g., using AWS Outposts).
AWS Example: VPC with private subnets and restricted access.

Hybrid Cloud
Definition: Combines public and private clouds to allow data and applications to be shared between them.
Characteristics:
Flexibility to move workloads.
Useful for disaster recovery, data residency, and gradual cloud migration.
AWS Example: On-premises data center connected to AWS via VPN or AWS Direct Connect.

Multi-Cloud
Definition: Use of multiple cloud providers (e.g., AWS + Azure + GCP).
Characteristics:
Avoid vendor lock-in.
Optimize services and pricing.
AWS Context: Integrating AWS services with other cloud platforms using APIs or third-party tools.

service models
üåê Cloud Service Models
Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)

What it provides: Virtualized computing resources over the internet (e.g., servers, storage, networking).
Examples: AWS EC2, Microsoft Azure VMs, Google Compute Engine.
Users manage: Applications, data, runtime, middleware, OS.

Platform as a Service (PaaS)
What it provides: A platform allowing customers to develop, run, and manage applications without dealing with infrastructure.
Examples: Google App Engine, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Microsoft Azure App Services.
Users manage: Applications and data.

Software as a Service (SaaS)
What it provides: Software applications delivered over the internet.
Examples: Gmail, Microsoft 365, Salesforce.
Users manage: Just the usage of the software.
